00:09:39.940 --> 00:09:46.430
I want to talk specifically about what I wrote
in the Heroes and Philosophy volume, and the

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:53.380
topic was on time and meaning in Nietzsche
and heroes. Time to me is such a philosophically

00:09:53.380 --> 00:09:59.030
interesting topic. I--our understanding of
time on the most like fundamental levels really

00:09:59.030 --> 00:10:07.600
does inform a lot of, who we are as people,
as human beings. Many philosophers have argued

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:12.560
that, you know, man or woman is essentially,
a temporal being that we define our existence

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:21.260
and/or identity in terms of time. On a less
like you know, lofty level like, we can pretty

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:26.320
much say that we are obsessed with time. Like,
to see how this possessiveness plays out,

00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:29.470
we just need to look at, you know--like think
about for a second, like the language that

00:10:29.470 --> 00:10:34.210
we use when we're talking about time. We're
always aware of the ways in which we spend

00:10:34.210 --> 00:10:38.930
our time. When we're enjoying ourselves, we
say that we're having the time of our life.

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:42.990
When we are disappointed with the outcome
of something, we say that was a waste of time.

00:10:42.990 --> 00:10:46.900
When we're at work, we say that we're on the
clock. When we are not at work, we say that

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:52.090
we're taking time off or we're on vacation
time and so on and so on, you like the idea.

00:10:52.090 --> 00:10:57.460
But like time has that, like omnipresent sort
of feature on our everyday lives, just count

00:10:57.460 --> 00:11:00.090
for instance the number of ways that you can
tell time, I've got my clock, I've got my

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:04.570
phone, I've got--there's a little time were
up here, but just think about in your home

00:11:04.570 --> 00:11:09.570
or your office, or your apartment or whatever
like the ways to tell time, the ways to measure

00:11:09.570 --> 00:11:14.661
time, or ways to be reminded of time are everywhere
on our--in on everything. So it's interesting,

00:11:14.661 --> 00:11:20.620
it's interesting to think about and, you know,
underlying that cause, it's almost like--I

00:11:20.620 --> 00:11:25.530
don't know what it's called, it almost like
in uncertainty or a feeling that if we're

00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:28.760
not paying attention to time, we're worried
that something is going to happen to us, or

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:33.040
some--that something is going to happen to
time, so there's that--that omnipresent awareness.

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:37.330
The only two places that you can't see reminders
of time, at least the ones that I could think

00:11:37.330 --> 00:11:39.320
of were the post office and casinos so the
places that you're wasting time the most are

00:11:39.320 --> 00:11:45.450
the places where you don't want to be reminded
of time. But anyways, that's sort of like

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:50.330
mindfulness of time and meaning is kind of
what, where I decided to write about and that

00:11:50.330 --> 00:11:56.531
it's certainly a major theme within Heroes.
Hiro, the character, you know, his super powers,

00:11:56.531 --> 00:12:01.391
the ability to stop time and to move backwards
and forwards through time. So there's that

00:12:01.391 --> 00:12:07.570
kind of, you know, sci-fi thought problem
that we can sort of, sort of play with. There's

00:12:07.570 --> 00:12:10.880
a moment in the show when Hiro--very early,
it's like the second or third episode. He's

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:17.380
trying to explain how his powers worked to
his friend Ando, and he said, "People think

00:12:17.380 --> 00:12:21.440
that time runs in a straight line," he draws
a straight line but he actually runs like

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:29.020
this, in a circle. So, that is extremely significant
to me I think in terms of, when I talk about

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:33.900
in the chapter on Nietzsche--the general premise
of Nietzsche's ideas is what he calls the

00:12:33.900 --> 00:12:39.710
eternal recurrence. That time isn't whinier,
the time doesn't necessarily run in a straight

00:12:39.710 --> 00:12:45.330
line but he wants us to think that time can
run over and over again in the fashion of

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:51.720
like a circle. He uses his idea of the eternal
recurrence ask us to imagine that our entire

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:57.490
life would recur over and over, and over again
in an endless loop of kind of this, you know,

00:12:57.490 --> 00:13:02.139
undifferentiated sameness. So, he ask us to
like actually think about this for a second,

00:13:02.139 --> 00:13:05.280
"What would you think like what would you
do, what would you response to this sort of

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:09.170
situation?" It's not like this is supposed
to be something that could or would happen,

00:13:09.170 --> 00:13:12.980
but he wants to do like, think in terms of
like, you know, how you view your life? Like,

00:13:12.980 --> 00:13:18.050
you know, if everything would repeat over
and over, and over again for all eternity.

00:13:18.050 --> 00:13:23.971
It supposed to be a thought problem and the
eternal recurrence--what Nietzsche's means

00:13:23.971 --> 00:13:27.840
by this is that, everything that has happened
and is happening and will happen, will happen

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:37.650
over and over, and over, and over again. When
we start to think about it in a minute, we're

00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:42.970
actually supposed to realize that this is
a horrible, horrible thing. In example from

00:13:42.970 --> 00:13:48.690
the show that I could illustrate this is at
the end of season two in hero--for those of

00:13:48.690 --> 00:13:54.180
you who have seen the episodes, he traps Adam
Monroe in a coffin. Adam Monroe is like the

00:13:54.180 --> 00:13:58.450
bad guy in season two but he's a person who,
you know, like his super powers is to live

00:13:58.450 --> 00:14:02.180
really long, so he's several hundred years
old. But, when you think about that for a

00:14:02.180 --> 00:14:07.050
second, being alive but stuck in a coffin
basically forever doing the same thing over

00:14:07.050 --> 00:14:11.040
and over again which is nothing, that is pretty
much the eternal recurrence in a nutshell,

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:15.150
that's like the--the awful weightiness that
Nietzsche wants to impress upon us. It's supposed

00:14:15.150 --> 00:14:21.150
to be awful, it's supposed to be that feeling
of unmitigated, you know, lack of change and

00:14:21.150 --> 00:14:25.430
no hope of there ever being a change. So,
it's a thought problem, it's kind of a downer

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:30.290
but that's what philosophy is sometimes. So,
Nietzsche and like I want to quote one of

00:14:30.290 --> 00:14:35.730
his works directly from the Gay Science, he
describes the situation in the following way.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:40.420
"There will be nothing new in it, but every
pain and every joy and every thought, and

00:14:40.420 --> 00:14:44.240
every sign, and everything and honorably small
and great in your life will have to return

00:14:44.240 --> 00:14:52.120
to you all in the same succession and sequence."
So, time and repetition are prominent themes

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:56.470
in the first season. When you think about
the--like the tag line, for what the show

00:14:56.470 --> 00:15:01.410
first became famous for, save the cheerleaders,
save the world, I mean the basic idea behind

00:15:01.410 --> 00:15:07.710
that was that, the future mustn't repeat itself
in the present. They saw this like, you know,

00:15:07.710 --> 00:15:11.240
post-apocalyptic thing that happens, New York
City blows up, and then they're supposed to

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:15.850
go back into the present to stop the future
from happening. So again, this time and repetition

00:15:15.850 --> 00:15:19.690
themes were very prominent in the show even
they're not necessarily spelled out in that

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:24.980
way. So it's clear in the show why we don't
want things to happen like that, why we don't

00:15:24.980 --> 00:15:31.920
want things to repeat. We don't want New York
City to blow up, so Hiro travels back in time.

00:15:31.920 --> 00:15:36.710
But for Nietzsche he puts to us the question,
"If we could change things to be other than

00:15:36.710 --> 00:15:41.410
they were, what does that tell us about ourselves?
Why would we want to do that? Why do we want

00:15:41.410 --> 00:15:48.570
thinks to change?" And I'm going to come back
and like try to offer an explanation for the

00:15:48.570 --> 00:15:55.570
answer. But, the way when we answer this question
kind of serves as, a way of providing some

00:15:55.570 --> 00:16:00.350
sort of insight to ourselves about how we
view our lives and how we view the sort of

00:16:00.350 --> 00:16:05.070
way everything should be connected. For Nietzsche,
we understand that a single moment can be

00:16:05.070 --> 00:16:10.791
like a fundamental measure of time. We find
moments, if you think about, you know, any

00:16:10.791 --> 00:16:16.000
moment in particular, moments are so valuable
because they are so pleading and so transient.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.901
Some people spent their whole lives trying
to pursue a lost moment or waiting for a moment

00:16:20.901 --> 00:16:27.000
that never happens. But the idea of the eternal
recurrence is that, what would you--how do

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:31.270
you feel about that moment? That, whatever
it is that you have schemed so highly, if

00:16:31.270 --> 00:16:35.051
that same thing were to happen over and over,
and over again, could you possibly like, you

00:16:35.051 --> 00:16:40.420
know, care as much about it were to repeat?
No, you couldn't, that's--by definition, it's

00:16:40.420 --> 00:16:45.250
that finitude that sense of, you know, fleetingness
that we find so valuable in which we derive

00:16:45.250 --> 00:16:52.720
the meaning and, you know, contentment from.
So, it--like, as a thought problem this idea

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:56.560
of everything recurring over and over again
is actually a very interesting one when you

00:16:56.560 --> 00:17:00.470
start to apply it to, you know, different
moments in time and different moment from

00:17:00.470 --> 00:17:06.470
your life. There's a clear parallel I think
in this regard that Nietzsche's philosophy,

