00:18:00.450 --> 00:18:05.130
the philosophy is there if we care to look
for it. Usually the philosophy isn't quite

00:18:05.130 --> 00:18:08.690
as transparent as the character like actually
holding the book--actually it's never that

00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:11.840
obvious. Is like a character holding a book
and saying like, you know, this is the philosophy

00:18:11.840 --> 00:18:16.210
that we're talking about, but it shows that
philosophy is present in a lot of ways if

00:18:16.210 --> 00:18:18.630
we, you know, cared to look for these things
and observe like those sort of details which

00:18:18.630 --> 00:18:23.751
is nice and that's why, you know, the approach
of, you know, not only Heroes and Philosophy

00:18:23.751 --> 00:18:31.290
but, a lot of similar popular culture in philosophy
books that are, are part of the series. In

00:18:31.290 --> 00:18:35.900
the end, the reason for bringing up all this
question about time and repetition, and meaning

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:39.059
is really just to have us consider like if
we think of things purely in terms of--oh,

00:18:39.059 --> 00:18:44.210
this is a good moment or this is a bad moment,
do we only think of things in those terms

00:18:44.210 --> 00:18:48.790
is/or sometimes can we actually see like a
larger sense of inner connection like, you

00:18:48.790 --> 00:18:53.280
know, see that one moment is actually necessary
for another moment, like that's not always

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:57.710
an easy thing to do. There's another very
interesting moment in that first season when

00:18:57.710 --> 00:19:02.260
Hiro's future self the--like the bad ass version
of himself, was like the goatee [ph] in a

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:06.570
ponytail and the sword and everything. He
has the string map like it's this very interesting--I

00:19:06.570 --> 00:19:11.780
forgot what he calls it other than like, like
this map of advance for like these things

00:19:11.780 --> 00:19:16.160
happen in time and he's got--oops, he's got
like strings attached to each of these things

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:20.590
and he says like, you know, this is a map
of time and you can trace like different events

00:19:20.590 --> 00:19:25.190
and different people, and where things fell
together, where things fell apart. So, that,

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:29.020
like it's a very fitting analogy I think for
what I'm trying to talk about in the--in the

00:19:29.020 --> 00:19:32.650
Nietzsche chapter that there is the sense
of like, you know, one single moment can be

00:19:32.650 --> 00:19:38.140
very interconnected. And a lot of times it's
impossible for us to kind of discern like,

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:42.390
you know, how these connections happened but
it's just--like as a metaphor, I just want

00:19:42.390 --> 00:19:46.280
you to think about that image of this like
string map with all of these different things.

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:49.720
What would your life look like if it were,
you know, like little push pins and strings,

00:19:49.720 --> 00:19:53.990
and like you connect people in events and
times, and everything together? Like I think

00:19:53.990 --> 00:20:00.230
that's a very, very appropriate way to kind
of understand what Nietzsche is talking about.

00:20:00.230 --> 00:20:04.010
So that's one of the things that, in terms
of philosophical questions that Heroes and

00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:09.530
Philosophy discusses. Another thing we should
dealt more into that I mentioned earlier is

00:20:09.530 --> 00:20:15.470
the question of good and evil. Are the heroes
really good? That doesn't really--I mean it

00:20:15.470 --> 00:20:20.640
sounds like a really obvious and banal question
but right around season three, things start

00:20:20.640 --> 00:20:26.040
to get less black and white. Heroes can become
villains and villains can sometimes become

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:30.650
heroes before quickly turning back to villains,
so there's that kind of, you know, again like

00:20:30.650 --> 00:20:37.570
more uncertainty and then now, or rather a
nice way I think is presented in the show

00:20:37.570 --> 00:20:41.500
is the logo. I'm ripping this off from one
of my co-authors but he'll forgive me. The

00:20:41.500 --> 00:20:47.520
Heroes' logo is--in eclipse of the sun, right,
and in Plato's Republic, Plato describe the

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:53.660
sun as basically as symbol for goodness and
knowledge, and like, you know, the intelligibility

00:20:53.660 --> 00:20:56.890
of goodness through like, you know, the light
of reason and all these things. If you think

00:20:56.890 --> 00:21:01.170
about an eclipse for instance, like the sense
of like, you know, there's something obscuring

00:21:01.170 --> 00:21:05.960
the sun, like it suppose to symbolize, could
symbolize, you know, like this sort of like

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:11.380
moral, uncertainty and ambiguity that happens
in the show. So, it's a very fitting metaphor

00:21:11.380 --> 00:21:18.920
I think. Without getting to, I think college
electuary for everyone, there--I would just

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:22.040
quickly say there are a number of ways that
philosophers have kind of dealt with this

00:21:22.040 --> 00:21:28.640
issue of, you know, good and evil, and like
in a ways which has been conceptualized. Socrates,

00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:33.420
for one felt that evil was basically, simply
resulting of insufficient knowledge that,

00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:37.309
you know, like everyone--anyone who really
understood what it meant to be good and to

00:21:37.309 --> 00:21:42.660
do good, would do good. Like evil and badness,
and more of wrongness was really just, you

00:21:42.660 --> 00:21:48.500
know, insufficient and understanding of what
good really was, that was Socrates'--that's

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:54.820
a thumbnail sketch what Socrates, you know,
felt was the, kind of the moral philosophy

00:21:54.820 --> 00:21:59.740
there. So, you know, evil wasn't so much evil
in the sake of evil but it was the, the results

00:21:59.740 --> 00:22:04.550
of the imperfect knowledge. Nietzsche and
another one of this were is called Beyond

00:22:04.550 --> 00:22:10.570
Good and Evil, asks us to think about why
we think of good and evil the way we do. And

00:22:10.570 --> 00:22:16.090
what he means by that is maybe definitions
of good and evil are as set as we think they

00:22:16.090 --> 00:22:23.760
are. He asks us just for the sake of argument
to consider a time when maybe evil meant then

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:29.040
what good means now, that there is this inversion
of swords between terms. Maybe there could

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:35.500
be an evolution from like, you know, like
what--he's asking us to consider what exactly

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:39.930
is the goodness of good and the evilness of
evil. One of the things that he talks about

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:43.001
without getting into too much more detail
about this was the, Nietzsche suggest that

00:22:43.001 --> 00:22:49.190
good and evil could possibly have started
from just like, you know, this means of differentiation

00:22:49.190 --> 00:22:53.880
that good and evil without any sort of like
moral evaluation would just simply be a way

00:22:53.880 --> 00:22:58.441
of saying, you know, goodness and evilness
could have been a term of like, you know,

00:22:58.441 --> 00:23:03.210
me-ness and you-ness. I call myself good,
therefore I call you bad because you're not

00:23:03.210 --> 00:23:07.400
me. So in a very like simple like, you know,
kindergarten level, like we understand intuitively

00:23:07.400 --> 00:23:14.070
why that could have been the way things were.
In season one, to kind of pick up the theme

00:23:14.070 --> 00:23:19.630
again of like more on uncertainty and sort
of like these shades of gray. There's a very

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:26.390
sort of Watchmen like plot for anyone that
seen the movie or the, read the graphic noble

00:23:26.390 --> 00:23:32.260
by Alan Moore, which again like I said results
and the blowing up in New York City. There

00:23:32.260 --> 00:23:36.130
are a few people who know that this is going
to happen but they choose not to do something

00:23:36.130 --> 00:23:43.010
about it. The moral justification is that
they're uniting humanity against the common

00:23:43.010 --> 00:23:48.150
threat and that's very Machiavellian sort
of--and to justify the means. And, at one

00:23:48.150 --> 00:23:52.660
point, one of the character says, "People
need hope but they trust fear" so this idea,

00:23:52.660 --> 00:23:56.320
and one of the episodes that's really good
and really kind of chilling and creepy is

00:23:56.320 --> 00:24:03.620
called .07%, and the idea is that .07% of
the human population is an unacceptable lost

00:24:03.620 --> 00:24:09.110
until I can ensure against like, greater like
you know catastrophe. So this idea that you

00:24:09.110 --> 00:24:13.250
blow up New York City and your, you know,
letting this many people to get blown up but

00:24:13.250 --> 00:24:16.960
and then, you know, they are going to go to
that spoiling episode that they're saving

00:24:16.960 --> 00:24:21.260
more lives in the process like for the future.
It's good, it's a really good episode and

00:24:21.260 --> 00:24:26.130
again, like the first season is--it touches
on like a whole slew; very philosophically

00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:32.130
interesting theories were all making for very
good drama I think. Interesting questions

00:24:32.130 --> 00:24:37.990
in moral ambiguity that, for me, that shows
you know narrative threat the first three

00:24:37.990 --> 00:24:43.210
seasons. And there's a difference I think
between moral ambiguity which is what I've

00:24:43.210 --> 00:24:46.801
been talking about and moral compromises.
That's another thing that one of the chapters

00:24:46.801 --> 00:24:52.550
in the book talks about Noah Bennett, who's
the horn-rimmed glasses guy. He does some

00:24:52.550 --> 00:24:57.780
pretty terrible things, including like torture
and murder, in the service of what he says,

00:24:57.780 --> 00:25:01.220
he's protecting his family which, you know,
like if you follow his character like, you

00:25:01.220 --> 00:25:07.870
know, that's very important to him is like,
you know, being a good father but it is a

00:25:07.870 --> 00:25:12.799
compromise. He's sacrificing some things like,
you know, like killing people and torturing

00:25:12.799 --> 00:25:18.330
people if it means protecting the people he
cares about the most. Angela Petrelli, justifies

00:25:18.330 --> 00:25:22.059
lighting--New York get blown up for the simple
reason that she considers it a greater good

00:25:22.059 --> 00:25:28.980
that's going to result in a better future
for everyone. Nathan Petrelli who's the son

00:25:28.980 --> 00:25:35.360
of Angela suggests that super power people's,
like, concentration camps would be a good

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:39.180
idea. It would be a good thing to protect
everyone else from themselves. So there's

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:44.590
this question that's a very politically freighted
argument obviously that liberty can be exchanged

00:25:44.590 --> 00:25:49.450
for security. So there's, you know, there's
a very interesting issues here, and on the

00:25:49.450 --> 00:25:53.400
one hand, some of these examples--some of
these are very whacked out examples. Some

00:25:53.400 --> 00:25:59.100
of them are not as whacked out as others which
make them disturbingly close to home. What

00:25:59.100 --> 00:26:04.679
this has to do with us, however, is this notion
again of like moral compromise is not unfamiliar

00:26:04.679 --> 00:26:09.650
to us in our every day lives. Maybe not these
specific instances but we understand intuitively

00:26:09.650 --> 00:26:14.900
what we, you know, we make trade offs in small
decisions where we're deciding one set of

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:19.130
moral values for another, and that's inevitable,
that's what we do in life whether we realize

00:26:19.130 --> 00:26:28.559
it or not. Heroes is also interesting to us.
One of the things, the reason for that is,

00:26:28.559 --> 00:26:32.000
in this book--and again, I'll talk about these
kind of shades of gray, this is kind of like

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:36.580
ambiguity between dark and light, black and
white, is that we take for granted this like

00:26:36.580 --> 00:26:42.440
black and white, these things between heroes
and villains, and good and bad. One of these

00:26:42.440 --> 00:26:46.520
moral sorts of question which I think is kind
of a neat one is: What effect do superpowers

00:26:46.520 --> 00:26:52.410
have on society? You know, it's kind of a
silly question but it does like, you know,

00:26:52.410 --> 00:26:58.210
it has intellectual merit I think because
if you think about, and we're not even talking

00:26:58.210 --> 00:27:02.130
about super powers anymore. How would you
act when you could do things that no one else

00:27:02.130 --> 00:27:09.510
could do and no one would be able to stop
you? Asking this kind of questions get some

00:27:09.510 --> 00:27:14.650
of the nature of morality, were we no longer
to have like the traditional suicidal checks

00:27:14.650 --> 00:27:18.960
of like, you know, discipline and punishment
and this sort of things. Then all are really

00:27:18.960 --> 00:27:23.100
is at that point is this moral obligation
to do what we think is right or what we think

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:29.559
is wrong. What would that look like in the
world of Heroes? There's an episode were they

00:27:29.559 --> 00:27:34.350
talk about this, but the idea that I'm kind
of hinting out here in short, is the idea

00:27:34.350 --> 00:27:40.390
of another philosopher, John Locke, not the
Lost character but the 17th century British

00:27:40.390 --> 00:27:46.220
Philosopher and his idea of the social contract.
The social contract basically says that, you

00:27:46.220 --> 00:27:51.280
know, Locke means to say, "We live in an orderly
society for a certain reasons." We have certain

00:27:51.280 --> 00:27:56.210
rules which we obey because in turn, you know,
we get protection from being innocent in our

00:27:56.210 --> 00:27:59.690
society, we're not killing everyone and stealing
each other all the time, that's the balance

00:27:59.690 --> 00:28:04.669
[ph]. You're sacrificing some amount of personal
freedom in order to get like the larger protection

00:28:04.669 --> 00:28:09.300
and the larger benefits of being part of a
society. Thomas Hobbes talks about this issue

00:28:09.300 --> 00:28:15.040
in his state of nature which is very similar
to this idea of the--the outcome of which

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:19.450
is the social contract. Where Heroes comes
in, I mean just for the sake of argument is

00:28:19.450 --> 00:28:24.020
what happens to the society when, you know,
let's say, what happens to the society and

00:28:24.020 --> 00:28:32.030
its rules when people--some people were no
longer need that, that protection or no longer

00:28:32.030 --> 00:28:37.970
have those rules of the society apply to them.
If such people like, you know, where do exist,

00:28:37.970 --> 00:28:42.840
like how they would exist, you know, forget
super power for a second but just think. If

00:28:42.840 --> 00:28:48.260
they didn't need society in the way that the
rest of us need society like, you know, would

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:52.280
or should, I mean for there, you know, from
their personal standpoint, will they need

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:56.660
to abide by the same rules that we do? It
gets in the questions, in a criminal justice

00:28:56.660 --> 00:29:01.540
and all these other things. But philosophers
like Hobbes and Locke, you know, when they

00:29:01.540 --> 00:29:04.929
speak about society, they bring up the fact,
the premises of the society is like there's

00:29:04.929 --> 00:29:09.370
a need for it. There's a need for society
because we are really more equal than, you

00:29:09.370 --> 00:29:14.250
know, sometimes we care to realize or care
to admit as like, you know, living human beings.

00:29:14.250 --> 00:29:19.910
In one episode of the show which is called
I Am Become Death, I think this is the fourth

00:29:19.910 --> 00:29:26.250
episode of the third season, and it's really
one of the neater episodes of the show. A

00:29:26.250 --> 00:29:30.610
super power formula kind of--is distributed
through in this kind of like alternate scenario

00:29:30.610 --> 00:29:36.060
and in effect everyone get super powers. And,
essentially, what happens, the result of this

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:41.049
is just a very dark future for everyone. Power
for everyone is much more a blessing than

00:29:41.049 --> 00:29:46.460
a curse--at least, that's the thesis that
that episode is sort of putting out there.

00:29:46.460 --> 00:29:51.360
Many of us have heard the often-used quote
which is from Lord Acton that power tends

00:29:51.360 --> 00:29:57.150
to corrupt--power tends to corrupt; absolute
power corrupts absolutely. And this seems

00:29:57.150 --> 00:30:01.450
to be, you know, kind of the case that, you
know, Heroes is, you know, suggesting in some

00:30:01.450 --> 00:30:05.570
of these episodes, similar episodes to the
one I just talked about. But power without

00:30:05.570 --> 00:30:12.260
the sort of like moral checks and balances
that society ensures is an extremely dangerous

00:30:12.260 --> 00:30:16.580
thing. Some of us would adhere to a moral
code just because that's the way we are and

00:30:16.580 --> 00:30:20.390
some of us would not, it's like, if this were
to be the case. Some of us would do whatever

00:30:20.390 --> 00:30:24.830
it is we wanted to do simply for the fact
that, you know, we could do it and get away

00:30:24.830 --> 00:30:28.080
with it. But it says something about like--you
know, these are questions of human nature

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:32.100
and these are questions about, you know, why
society is important and why society functions

00:30:32.100 --> 00:30:38.179
the way it is. So, again, like the--the idea
here is that there are interesting scenarios.

00:30:38.179 --> 00:30:43.710
Like, they seem very, you know, farfetched
sometimes. When we start to actually think

00:30:43.710 --> 00:30:47.490
about it, we can see some of these issues
and like, you know, it causes us, like, you

00:30:47.490 --> 00:30:53.460
know, hopefully it causes us to reflect on
some of these deeper things. Speaking of ethics

00:30:53.460 --> 00:30:57.210
and this question of right and wrong, there's
one more topic I want to talk about in terms

00:30:57.210 --> 00:31:01.960
of Heroes before we kind of open it up to
questions and everything. Really, like, I

00:31:01.960 --> 00:31:06.490
think devotees of the history of the show
will probably be familiar with this. This

00:31:06.490 --> 00:31:12.280
is the question of Heroes as a show and the
question of originality. People have said

00:31:12.280 --> 00:31:16.070
in, like, you know, in the past that, "Oh,
the plot for Heroes is like, you know, the

00:31:16.070 --> 00:31:20.850
issue of Uncanny X-Men number 143," where,
like, you know, there's, like, dystopian,

00:31:20.850 --> 00:31:25.120
like, you know, history where--excuse me,
not history--future, alternate future were

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:30.580
everyone dies and then someone has to go back
in time to save them. I mean if you follow

00:31:30.580 --> 00:31:34.030
the first, like, you know, first, second and
third season of the show, like, you know,

00:31:34.030 --> 00:31:39.270
yeah, that kind of is the show in a nutshell.
Like there is this, like, you know, premise

00:31:39.270 --> 00:31:44.900
that is very much like, you know, other comic
book plots that have been done before Heroes.

00:31:44.900 --> 00:31:50.220
On the one hand--so the issue that we're getting
at is again like creativity versus originality

00:31:50.220 --> 00:31:54.230
here. Many people have wondered why there
are so many similarities between Heroes and

00:31:54.230 --> 00:31:58.830
the X-Men. This is one of the chapters of
the book and it's kind of fun chapter to read.

00:31:58.830 --> 00:32:05.039
Many of the powers in the show are similar
to X-Men. Claire's healing powers are like

00:32:05.039 --> 00:32:11.380
Wolverine's healing deal. There's like a guy
who, you know, controls metal like Magneto

00:32:11.380 --> 00:32:16.610
does. There's Sylar's like, you know, power-stealing
thing just like Rogue from the X-Men. It goes

00:32:16.610 --> 00:32:25.210
on and on and on. So we can also argue--and,
like, this is the other side of the coin--that

00:32:25.210 --> 00:32:29.480
old stories can be told and retold in different
ways and possibly new and illuminating ways,

00:32:29.480 --> 00:32:35.809
and, you know, such is the nature of stories.
They're told and told again and perhaps something

00:32:35.809 --> 00:32:41.620
is added or something is taken away. So, this
question about originality and, like, you

00:32:41.620 --> 00:32:45.520
know, whether this is, you know, like a form
of plagiarism or something, like on one level,

00:32:45.520 --> 00:32:49.290
like a very, like, a basic functional level
is interesting and, like, you know, I'll be

00:32:49.290 --> 00:32:53.071
honest, I wouldn't be happy if someone, like,
took my ideas in writing and, like, passed

00:32:53.071 --> 00:32:59.110
it off as their own which, you know, is nowadays
what they call academic writing--I'm just

00:32:59.110 --> 00:33:03.390
kidding. The question is not that straightforward
though. It's actually more than like, you

00:33:03.390 --> 00:33:07.950
know, when we get past this later of like,
oh, this is just a rip-off of the X-Men, we

00:33:07.950 --> 00:33:13.200
start to really think about deeper issues
and one of the things that the chapter talks

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:18.360
about is this question of epistemic responsibility
which is--it's a fancy way of saying, like,

00:33:18.360 --> 00:33:20.860
you know, do we--what responsibility do we
have to know things, like to have knowledge

00:33:20.860 --> 00:33:27.580
and to, like, you know, be more knowledgeable
about things that we should know about. So,

00:33:27.580 --> 00:33:31.570
you know, example, like if you're writing
a show on superheroes, should you know something

00:33:31.570 --> 00:33:37.701
about the superhero genre. If you're creating
a show like Heroes, does that--does it seem

00:33:37.701 --> 00:33:41.630
a little disingenuous to say, like, I don't
read comic books because I'd be worried that

00:33:41.630 --> 00:33:46.190
someone had already thought of my own ideas
and I don't want to know that. That's not

